HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 845
By Hakeem
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Representative Tommie
F. Brown of Chattanooga.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of our friend and former colleague Representative Tommie F. Brown of
Chattanooga; and
WHEREAS, a courageous community leader who left her mark on the political
landscape of both Chattanooga and the State of Tennessee, Representative Tommie Brown
faithfully and honorably served the people of Hamilton County's 28th House District as a member
of the 98th, 99th, 100th, 101st, 102nd, 103rd, 104th, 105th, 106th, and 107th General Assemblies; and
WHEREAS, a trailblazing professional in higher education, Dr. Tommie Brown earned a
Bachelor of Arts degree from B.A. Dillard University, a Master of Social Work degree from
Washington University, and a Doctorate of Social Work from Columbia University; and
WHEREAS, in 1971, Dr. Brown joined the faculty at the University of Tennessee at
Chattanooga, where she founded the Social Work program and later became the first African-
American woman to serve as a department head; for decades she shaped minds and hearts,
training generations of social workers, mentors, and leaders who would carry forward her belief
that knowledge is power and service is a duty; and
WHEREAS, putting her beliefs in action, Representative Brown was the lead plaintiff in
Brown v. City of Chattanooga, and she stood unwavering in the fight against an at-large election
system that had long diluted Black voting power; this effort transformed Chattanooga's
government into a mayor–council system with district-based elections, finally ensuring that
communities of color had representation; and
