WHEREAS, as a member of the General Assembly, she sponsored legislation
addressing education, health, racial discrimination, children's rights, and voting rights; she also
helped organize community efforts and civic leadership networks across the State; and
WHEREAS, Representative Brown was among the individuals who called for a complete
overhaul of Tennessee's foster care system, demanding better health care and services for
children in state custody, and her efforts led to the history and contributions of Tennessee's first
African-American legislators being preserved by the Tennessee State Library and Archives and
made available online; and
WHEREAS, Representative Brown served with impeccable statesmanship throughout
her legislative tenure, during which she rendered sterling service as a member of the House
State and Local Government Committee; House Finance, Ways and Means Committee; House
General Subcommittee of the State and Local Committee; House and Senate Joint Fiscal
Review Committee; House Calendar and Rules Committee; House Children and Family Affairs
Committee; House K-12 Subcommittee; House Education Special Initiatives Subcommittee;
House Domestic Relations Subcommittee; House and Senate Joint Education Oversight
Subcommittee; Joint Select Committee on Children and Youth; Joint Select Committee on
Pensions and Insurance; Joint Lottery Scholarship Committee; Diabetes Prevention Study
Committee; and Title VI Compliance Review Commission; and
WHEREAS, respected for her leadership abilities, Representative Brown was chosen to
serve as the vice chair of the House Education Committee, the chair of the House Higher
Education Subcommittee, and the chair of the Tennessee Black Caucus of State Legislators;
and
WHEREAS, a highly-valued member of her community, Representative Brown dedicated
her time and energies to a number of civic organizations and endeavors, including the
Chattanooga Chapter of the National Political Congress of Black Women, which she co-
founded; the Hamilton County Democratic Women's Club; the Pi Omega Chapter of the Alpha
Kappa Alpha Sorority; the Education Equal Opportunity Group, Inc., for which she served as a
- 2 - 012030

board member; and the Southeast Tennessee Development District, for which she served as an
executive board member; and
WHEREAS, in 2002, Hamilton County Schools named a school in her honor, the Dr.
Tommie F. Brown Academy for Classical Studies; and
WHEREAS, after her retirement from public service, Representative Brown remained
active by advocating for issues that uplifted her community, helping build coalitions to address
pressing issues, and continuing to mentor the leaders of tomorrow; and
WHEREAS, Representative Tommie Brown's legacy is living proof that courage and
dedication can reshape institutions, lift communities, and make the world better a better place
than we found it. She leaves a city that is more just, a state that is more accountable, and a
history that will preserve the work of a woman who devoted her life to service; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Tommie F. Brown, reflecting fondly upon her
legacy of service to the people of Tennessee and her stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Representative Brown.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
